<h1 class="hero-h">How much does a fractional COO cost? <em>The practical answer.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">A plain-English breakdown of what fractional COOs charge in 2026: the pricing models, what actually drives the number, and how it compares to a full-time operations hire.</p>
<div class="verdict"><div class="verdict-l">Short answer</div><p class="verdict-p">Fractional COOs charge $10K to $25K per month for one to two days per week, billed as a flat retainer. Hourly work runs $250 to $450 per hour. A full-time COO, by comparison, costs $350K to $600K all-in per year.</p></div>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">The three ways fractional COOs price</h2>
<p class="body">A fractional COO sells operational leadership and time, not a license. In 2026, three pricing models dominate:</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Monthly retainer ($10K to $25K / month).</strong> The standard. You agree on a set cadence (usually one to two days a week) and pay a flat fee. Predictable, and it keeps the COO embedded in the business rather than watching a clock.</li>
<li><strong>Hourly ($250 to $450 / hour).</strong> For lighter or variable workloads. Flexible, but harder to budget and less suited to a role that thrives on continuity.</li>
<li><strong>Project / fixed fee.</strong> A defined scope such as a systems implementation, an operational turnaround, or post-acquisition integration, priced as one number.</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">Because operations are continuous, most $5M to $50M companies choose the monthly retainer. For the cross-role view, see the <a href="/fractional-executive-pricing-guide-2026">fractional executive pricing guide for 2026</a>.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Why a COO often costs a bit more than a CFO</h2>
<p class="body">Fractional COO retainers tend to sit slightly above <a href="/how-much-does-a-fractional-cfo-cost">fractional CFO pricing</a> for a simple reason: the mandate is usually broader and more hands-on. A CFO owns a defined domain (finance). A COO frequently touches operations, systems, hiring, vendor management, and cross-functional execution all at once. That breadth tends to demand more days per week and a senior generalist who can move across the whole business, which nudges the fee up.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">What drives the number up or down</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Hours per week.</strong> The biggest lever. Two days a week roughly doubles a one-day engagement.</li>
<li><strong>Company complexity.</strong> Headcount, number of locations or product lines, and how mature your systems and processes already are.</li>
<li><strong>Phase.</strong> A turnaround or a fast-scaling phase is more intense, and more expensive, than steady-state process improvement.</li>
<li><strong>Active events.</strong> An ERP migration, a relocation, or integrating an acquisition raises both hours and seniority.</li>
<li><strong>Seniority.</strong> An operator who has scaled a company from $10M to $100M costs more than one who has run a single department.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Fractional COO vs. the alternatives</h2>
<p class="body">The fractional COO sits between a project consultant and a full-time operations chief. Here is the 2026 cost ladder.</p>
<table class="compare-table">
<thead><tr><th>Option</th><th>Typical cost</th><th>Best when</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Operations manager</td><td>$90K to $140K / year</td><td>You need someone to run existing processes day to day</td></tr>
<tr><td>Management consultant</td><td>$300 to $600 / hour</td><td>You need a defined project or analysis, then they leave</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fractional COO</td><td>$10K to $25K / month</td><td>You need senior operational leadership without a full-time salary</td></tr>
<tr><td>Full-time COO</td><td>$350K to $600K / year all-in</td><td>Operations are complex enough to need a dedicated executive</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p class="body">A consultant hands you a plan. A fractional COO owns the plan and makes it happen, sitting in your leadership meetings and accountable for whether the company actually runs better. That ownership is the difference you are paying for.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">What you actually get for the money</h2>
<p class="body">A fractional COO retainer typically covers the operational backbone of the company:</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li>Operational strategy and the systems to run it</li>
<li>Process design, documentation, and KPI dashboards</li>
<li>Cross-functional execution across sales, marketing, finance, and delivery</li>
<li>Hiring plans and team structure for operations roles</li>
<li>Vendor, tooling, and supply or service-delivery management</li>
<li>Turnaround, scaling, or integration leadership when the moment calls for it</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">A 2026 operator also brings automation leverage. Much of the reporting, documentation, and coordination that used to eat days can now be compressed with AI. See <a href="/how-to-use-claude-as-a-coo">how to use Claude as a COO</a> and the broader <a href="/ai-for-coos">AI toolkit for operations leaders</a>. If marketing and revenue operations are part of the mandate, a <a href="/revenue-operations-consultant">revenue operations consultant</a> often works alongside the COO.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Is it worth it?</h2>
<p class="body">Run the opportunity-cost test. A fractional COO at $15K per month is $180K a year. If that operator frees the founder from daily firefighting, fixes the systems that are capping growth, and makes execution reliable, the return is easy to justify. If operations are simple and running smoothly, hold off. The model pays for itself when execution becomes the bottleneck on growth. For how this lands across the other roles, compare <a href="/how-much-does-a-fractional-cmo-cost">fractional CMO cost</a> and <a href="/how-much-does-a-fractional-cfo-cost">fractional CFO cost</a>.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">How much does a fractional COO cost in 2026?</div><div class="faq-a">$10K to $25K per month for one to two days per week, or $250 to $450 per hour for hourly work. Turnarounds and integrations can run higher.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Why does a fractional COO cost more than a fractional CFO?</div><div class="faq-a">The COO mandate is usually broader and more hands-on, spanning operations, systems, hiring, and cross-functional execution at once. That breadth tends to demand more days per week and a senior generalist.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Is a fractional COO cheaper than a full-time COO?</div><div class="faq-a">Yes. A full-time COO costs $350K to $600K all-in. A fractional COO delivers senior operational leadership for roughly 25 to 50 percent of that, because you pay only for the days you need.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Retainer or hourly: which is better?</div><div class="faq-a">A monthly retainer suits the continuous nature of operations and keeps the COO embedded. Hourly fits light or variable work; fixed fees suit defined projects like a systems migration.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">When should I hire a fractional COO?</div><div class="faq-a">When the founder is buried in operations and execution is slipping, when you are scaling faster than your systems can handle, or when you need to professionalize operations ahead of a raise or sale.</div></div>
</div>
</div></section>

